INSERT INTO flashcards (course_id, question_text, answer_text, difficulty, order_index) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is a COSHH assessment?', 'A COSHH (Control of Substances Hazardous to Health) assessment is required under the COSHH Regulations 2002. It identifies hazardous substances used in the workplace (e.g. cleaning chemicals, body fluids, medication), assesses the risk of harm, and specifies control measures — such as ventilation, PPE, safe storage, and emergency procedures. Assessments must be reviewed regularly and whenever practices change.', 2, 26),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What does RIDDOR stand for and what must be reported?', 'RIDDOR stands for Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrences Regulations 2013. Employers must report to the Health and Safety Executive (HSE): work-related deaths; specified injuries (e.g. fractures other than fingers/toes, amputations, crush injuries); over-seven-day incapacitation injuries; work-related diseases (e.g. occupational dermatitis, carpal tunnel syndrome); and dangerous occurrences (near misses with potential for serious injury).', 2, 27),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is a near miss?', 'A near miss is an unplanned event that did not result in injury, illness, or damage but had the potential to do so. Reporting near misses is vital because they reveal hazards before harm occurs. Under RIDDOR, certain dangerous occurrences (near misses with high potential) must be reported to the HSE. Locally, near misses should always be recorded in the accident book and investigated to prevent recurrence.', 1, 28),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What are the five steps of risk assessment?', 'The five steps (as outlined by the HSE) are: (1) Identify the hazards; (2) Decide who might be harmed and how; (3) Evaluate the risks and decide on control measures; (4) Record your findings and implement them; (5) Review the assessment and update if necessary. Risk assessments must be "suitable and sufficient" and must be recorded if an organisation has five or more employees.', 1, 29),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is the difference between a hazard and a risk?', 'A hazard is anything with the potential to cause harm — for example, a wet floor, a chemical, or a heavy load. A risk is the likelihood that the hazard will actually cause harm, combined with the severity of that harm. Risk = Likelihood × Severity. Risk assessment involves identifying hazards and then evaluating and controlling the associated risks to an acceptable level.', 1, 30),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What are the key duties placed on employers under the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974?', 'Section 2 of the HASAW Act requires employers to, so far as is reasonably practicable: provide safe systems of work; maintain safe plant and equipment; ensure safe handling, storage, and transport of substances; provide information, instruction, training, and supervision; maintain a safe working environment with adequate welfare facilities; and prepare a written Health and Safety policy (for organisations with five or more employees).', 2, 31),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is the role of the Health and Safety Executive (HSE)?', 'The HSE is the national regulator for health and safety in the workplace in Great Britain, working under the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974. It develops and enforces health and safety law, publishes guidance and codes of practice, investigates serious accidents and work-related deaths, and can issue improvement notices, prohibition notices, or prosecute organisations and individuals for breaches. Local authorities share enforcement in lower-risk premises such as offices and shops.', 2, 32),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'How is work-related stress managed under health and safety law?', 'Work-related stress is a significant cause of absence. Under the Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999, employers must assess all risks including psychosocial risks. The HSE''s Management Standards identify six key areas: demands, control, support, relationships, role, and change. Employers should conduct a stress risk assessment, implement controls (e.g. reasonable workloads, supportive management), and provide access to occupational health and EAP.', 3, 33),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is the hierarchy of controls for managing hazards?', 'The hierarchy (most to least effective) is: (1) Elimination — remove the hazard entirely; (2) Substitution — replace with something less hazardous; (3) Engineering controls — isolate people from the hazard (e.g. guarding, ventilation); (4) Administrative controls — change working practices (e.g. training, rotas, signage); (5) Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) — last resort, protecting the individual. PPE is least preferred because it relies on correct use at all times.', 2, 34),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Which injuries and incidents must be reported to the HSE under RIDDOR 2013?', 'Reportable items include: work-related fatalities; specified injuries (fractures other than fingers/thumbs/toes; amputations; permanent loss of sight; crush injuries causing internal organ damage; serious burns; scalping; loss of consciousness from head injury/asphyxia; spinal injuries); injuries causing over-seven-day absence; work-related diseases (e.g. carpal tunnel, occupational asthma); and dangerous occurrences from a defined list (e.g. scaffold collapse, train derailment).', 3, 35),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What should a lone working risk assessment cover?', 'A lone working risk assessment should consider: the nature of the tasks (e.g. home visits, working alone late); the environment (remote location, vulnerable clients); the likelihood of violence or aggression; emergency procedures (what to do if the worker does not check in); communication arrangements (buddy systems, lone worker devices, regular check-in calls); training; and specific risks such as working with hazardous substances alone or undertaking manual handling without assistance.', 2, 36),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What are the duties of employees under the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974?', 'Section 7 of the HASAW Act requires employees to: take reasonable care for their own health and safety and that of others who may be affected by their acts or omissions; and cooperate with their employer on health and safety matters. Section 8 prohibits intentionally or recklessly interfering with or misusing anything provided for health and safety. Employees can also be prosecuted for breaches.', 2, 37),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is a dynamic risk assessment?', 'A dynamic risk assessment is an ongoing, real-time assessment of risk carried out as circumstances change, particularly in unpredictable environments such as home visits or community care. It involves continuously observing and evaluating situations, identifying new hazards, and adjusting working practices accordingly without stopping to complete a written form. It complements but does not replace formal written risk assessments.', 2, 38),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is an accident book and why must it be maintained?', 'An accident book (or incident log) is a legal requirement under the Social Security (Claims and Payments) Regulations 1979 for employers with ten or more employees. All work-related injuries and incidents must be recorded, including the date, location, nature of injury, and circumstances. Records support RIDDOR reporting, identify patterns, inform risk assessment reviews, and provide evidence in the event of compensation claims.', 1, 39),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Why is induction training important for health and safety?', 'Induction training ensures new workers understand the health and safety policies, emergency procedures (including fire evacuation), reporting processes, specific hazards in their role, use of equipment, manual handling, and PPE requirements before they begin work. The Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999 require employers to provide comprehensible and relevant information on risks and controls — induction is the first step in this ongoing obligation.', 1, 40),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What do the Working Time Regulations 1998 require?', 'The Working Time Regulations 1998 (implementing the EU Working Time Directive) provide: a maximum average 48-hour working week (workers may opt out in writing); a minimum of 11 hours'' rest between working days; a 20-minute break when working more than 6 hours; a minimum of one day off per week; and a minimum of 5.6 weeks'' paid annual leave. Night workers are limited to an average of 8 hours per night shift. These protections are particularly important in care settings where fatigue affects patient safety.', 2, 41),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is a DSE assessment and when is it required?', 'A Display Screen Equipment (DSE) assessment is required under the Health and Safety (Display Screen Equipment) Regulations 1992 for habitual users of computers, tablets, and similar screens. The assessment covers: screen position and height; keyboard and mouse use; chair adjustment; lighting and glare; and breaks from screen work. Employers must provide eye tests on request and corrective glasses if required solely for DSE work.', 2, 42),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is risk control in practice?', 'Risk control means implementing the measures identified in a risk assessment to reduce risk to an acceptable (ALARP — as low as reasonably practicable) level. Controls should follow the hierarchy: elimination, substitution, engineering controls, administrative controls, and PPE. Controls must be monitored for effectiveness, staff must be trained in them, and they must be reviewed when circumstances change or following an incident.', 2, 43),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is an environmental risk assessment in a care setting?', 'An environmental risk assessment considers the physical care environment for hazards that could harm residents, service users, or staff — including: trip and slip hazards (wet floors, loose carpets, poor lighting); bed and stair safety; outdoor areas; temperature extremes; access and egress; security risks; and infection control environments. It should be carried out by competent persons, documented, and reviewed regularly or following any incident.', 2, 44),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is duty of care in health and safety?', 'Duty of care is both a legal and ethical obligation to take reasonable steps to prevent harm to those who could foreseeably be affected by your actions or omissions. In health and safety law, employers owe a duty of care to employees and non-employees (visitors, contractors, service users). Employees also owe a duty of care to colleagues and service users. A breach of duty of care that causes harm may give rise to civil liability in negligence.', 2, 45),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What does "reasonably practicable" mean in health and safety law?', '"Reasonably practicable" (used throughout the HASAW Act) means balancing the risk against the sacrifice (time, cost, effort) needed to address it. If the risk is very low relative to the cost of control measures, it may not be reasonably practicable to implement them. If the risk is high, substantial cost and effort may still be required. This is a higher standard than "physically possible" — duty holders must actively demonstrate compliance.', 3, 46),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What are the key manual handling risk factors identified by the HSE?', 'The HSE uses the TILE acronym: Task (pushing, pulling, twisting, prolonged holding); Individual (health, fitness, training, pregnancy); Load (heavy, bulky, hard to grip, unstable, hazardous); Environment (space constraints, uneven floors, poor lighting, temperature). The Manual Handling Operations Regulations 1992 require employers to avoid manual handling where reasonably practicable, assess unavoidable operations, and reduce risk to the lowest reasonably practicable level.', 2, 47),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is safety culture?', 'Safety culture describes the shared values, attitudes, perceptions, competencies, and patterns of behaviour that determine an organisation''s commitment to health and safety. A positive safety culture is characterised by open reporting without blame, visible leadership commitment, worker involvement in safety decisions, and continuous learning from incidents. Poor safety culture is a root cause of many serious accidents. Managers must model safe behaviours to embed a positive safety culture.', 3, 48),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What welfare facilities must employers provide under health and safety law?', 'The Workplace (Health, Safety and Welfare) Regulations 1992 require employers to provide: adequate toilet and washing facilities (including hot water, soap, and towels); drinking water; a rest area (including facilities for pregnant women and nursing mothers); a place to eat meals; facilities for changing and storing clothing; and seating appropriate to the work. Welfare facilities must be maintained in a clean and serviceable condition.', 1, 49),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is the HASAW Act employer duty regarding health and safety policy?', 'Section 2(3) of the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974 requires employers with five or more employees to prepare, and bring to the attention of all employees, a written Health and Safety policy. The policy must include: a general statement of intent; the organisation (who is responsible for what); and the arrangements (how policy is implemented in practice). It must be reviewed regularly and when significant changes occur.', 2, 50)
INSERT INTO quiz_questions (course_id, question_text, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_option, explanation) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Under RIDDOR 2013, how long must an injury prevent a worker from performing their normal duties before it becomes reportable to the HSE?', 'More than 3 days', 'More than 7 days', 'More than 5 days', 'More than 14 days', 'B', 'Under RIDDOR 2013, a work-related injury that results in a worker being incapacitated and unable to perform their usual work duties for more than seven consecutive days (not counting the day of the injury itself) must be reported to the HSE. This is separate from the "over-three-day" incapacitation rule that previously existed before the 2013 revision, though employers must still keep a record of over-three-day injuries internally.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is the correct sequence of the five steps of risk assessment as defined by the HSE?', 'Identify hazards; evaluate risks; record findings; review; decide on controls', 'Identify hazards; decide who might be harmed and how; evaluate risks and decide on controls; record findings; review and update', 'Decide on controls; identify hazards; record findings; evaluate risks; review', 'Record findings; identify hazards; decide who might be harmed; evaluate risks; review', 'B', 'The HSE''s five steps to risk assessment are: (1) Identify the hazards; (2) Decide who might be harmed and how; (3) Evaluate the risks and decide on precautions; (4) Record your findings and implement them; (5) Review your assessment and update if necessary. This systematic approach ensures all relevant hazards are considered, appropriate people are protected, and controls are properly documented and kept current.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'In the hierarchy of controls, which measure is considered the MOST effective for managing a hazard?', 'Providing Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)', 'Administrative controls such as training and signage', 'Engineering controls such as guarding and ventilation', 'Elimination of the hazard', 'D', 'Elimination — physically removing the hazard — is at the top of the hierarchy because it completely removes the risk rather than merely managing it. Lower-level controls, such as PPE, are less effective because they rely on correct and consistent use by workers. The hierarchy progresses: Elimination > Substitution > Engineering Controls > Administrative Controls > PPE. In practice, a combination of controls is often necessary.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What do the COSHH Regulations 2002 require employers to do?', 'Only purchase substances with a COSHH-approved label', 'Assess the risks from hazardous substances and implement suitable controls to protect workers'' health', 'Prohibit the use of all chemical cleaning products in healthcare settings', 'Report all use of hazardous substances to the HSE', 'B', 'The COSHH Regulations 2002 require employers to: assess the risk to health from hazardous substances used in or arising from the workplace; prevent or adequately control that exposure; and ensure controls are used, maintained, and monitored. In care settings, COSHH applies to cleaning chemicals, disinfectants, and biological agents (including blood and body fluids). Data sheets and COSHH assessments must be available and staff must be trained.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Which of the following is a HAZARD, not a risk?', 'The probability that a wet floor will cause a slip', 'A bottle of bleach stored in an unlocked cupboard accessible to service users', 'The likelihood that a heavy patient will injure a carer during moving and handling', 'The chance that inadequate lighting will cause a trip', 'B', 'A hazard is something with the potential to cause harm — in this case, bleach accessible to service users is a hazardous substance and a physical hazard. The other options describe risks (likelihood of harm from a hazard). Understanding this distinction is fundamental to risk assessment: you first identify hazards, then assess the risk (likelihood and severity of harm) that each hazard presents, and then decide on controls.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Which of the following is a key requirement for lone workers in a care setting?', 'Lone workers are not permitted to carry out personal care tasks', 'A lone working risk assessment should be in place and regular check-in procedures established', 'All lone workers must carry a personal alarm at all times regardless of the risk assessment', 'Lone workers must always have a qualified first aider with them', 'B', 'The Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999 require employers to assess all risks, including those specific to lone workers. Key requirements include a suitable risk assessment, regular contact/check-in systems, emergency procedures, and appropriate training. The specific controls — such as personal alarms, buddy systems, or check-in calls — should be determined by the risk assessment rather than applying the same measure universally.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What does the TILE acronym stand for in manual handling risk assessment?', 'Task, Individual, Load, Equipment', 'Task, Individual, Load, Environment', 'Transfer, Injury, Lifting, Equipment', 'Training, Implementation, Legislation, Evidence', 'B', 'TILE stands for Task (what movements are required), Individual (the person doing the handling — their fitness, training, and any health conditions), Load (the characteristics of what is being moved — weight, size, stability, handles), and Environment (the space, flooring, lighting, and temperature). The Manual Handling Operations Regulations 1992 require employers to avoid manual handling where reasonably practicable and to assess and reduce risk where handling cannot be avoided.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What must an employer provide under the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974?', 'A safe system of work, safe equipment, and information, instruction, training, and supervision — so far as is reasonably practicable', 'A risk-free workplace with no hazards of any kind', 'Individual written risk assessments for every task every employee performs', 'Annual health surveillance for all employees regardless of role', 'A', 'Section 2 of the HASAW Act 1974 requires employers to ensure, so far as is reasonably practicable: safe plant and systems of work; safe use, handling, and storage of substances; adequate information, instruction, training, and supervision; a safe workplace with safe access and egress; and a suitable working environment with adequate welfare facilities. The phrase "reasonably practicable" allows a balance between the level of risk and the sacrifice required to address it.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is a near miss?', 'An incident that resulted in minor injury only', 'An unplanned event that did not result in harm but had the potential to do so', 'A hazard that has been identified but not yet controlled', 'An incident involving a near collision between two vehicles', 'B', 'A near miss is an unplanned event that did not result in injury, damage, or loss but clearly had the potential to do so. Reporting and investigating near misses is important because they represent a free lesson — they highlight systemic weaknesses before harm occurs. The HSE''s accident triangle (based on Heinrich''s work) suggests that for every serious injury there are many minor injuries and near misses, all with common root causes.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is the primary role of the Health and Safety Executive (HSE)?', 'To provide compensation to workers injured in the workplace', 'To regulate and enforce health and safety law in Great Britain', 'To manage the NHS health and safety programme', 'To investigate criminal offences in the workplace', 'B', 'The HSE is the national independent regulator for workplace health and safety in Great Britain. It works to prevent work-related death, injury, and ill health. Its functions include: making and enforcing regulations; publishing guidance; investigating major incidents; and prosecuting organisations and individuals for serious breaches. The HSE shares enforcement responsibilities with local authorities in lower-risk settings. It operates under the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'When should a risk assessment be reviewed?', 'Only when a new member of staff joins the team', 'Only every five years as a legal requirement', 'When there is reason to believe it is no longer valid, after a significant change, or following an incident', 'Whenever a member of staff requests a review', 'C', 'The Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999 require risk assessments to be reviewed when there is reason to believe they may no longer be valid or when there has been a significant change in the matters to which they relate. Best practice also involves reviewing following an incident or near miss, when new equipment or substances are introduced, following changes in legislation, and at regular planned intervals (the frequency depending on the level of risk).'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'A worker uses a computer workstation for most of their working day. Under which legislation are they entitled to a workstation assessment?', 'The Manual Handling Operations Regulations 1992', 'The Workplace (Health, Safety and Welfare) Regulations 1992', 'The Health and Safety (Display Screen Equipment) Regulations 1992', 'The Personal Protective Equipment at Work Regulations 1992', 'C', 'Habitual users of display screen equipment (DSE) have specific protections under the Health and Safety (Display Screen Equipment) Regulations 1992. Employers must: assess workstations and reduce risks; ensure adequate breaks or changes of activity; provide eye tests on request and corrective spectacles if needed solely for DSE; and provide training. The assessment covers screen position, lighting, chair adjustment, and keyboard/mouse use.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'What is the maximum average working week for adult workers under the Working Time Regulations 1998?', '40 hours per week', '48 hours per week', '60 hours per week', '35 hours per week', 'B', 'The Working Time Regulations 1998 set a maximum average working week of 48 hours, calculated over a reference period (normally 17 weeks). Workers may voluntarily opt out of this limit in writing, and this is relatively common in some care settings. However, other protections — such as daily rest periods (11 hours), weekly rest days (1 day per week), and break entitlements (20 minutes when working more than 6 hours) — cannot be opted out of.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Which of the following best describes the legal concept of "duty of care" in a health and safety context?', 'The duty to report every minor hazard to the HSE immediately', 'The obligation to take reasonable steps to avoid causing harm to those foreseeably affected by your actions', 'The requirement for managers to sign off every risk assessment personally', 'The obligation to provide PPE for all staff regardless of the risk level', 'B', 'Duty of care is a fundamental principle of negligence law, established in Donoghue v Stevenson [1932]. In health and safety, both employers and employees have a duty to take reasonable care to avoid acts or omissions that could reasonably be expected to harm others. A breach of duty that causes harm (where causation and damage can be proved) may give rise to a claim in negligence. In care settings, duty of care extends to service users, colleagues, visitors, and contractors.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Which regulations specify the welfare facilities an employer must provide?', 'The Health and Safety at Work Act 1974, Section 2', 'The Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999', 'The Workplace (Health, Safety and Welfare) Regulations 1992', 'The Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations 1998', 'C', 'The Workplace (Health, Safety and Welfare) Regulations 1992 set out detailed requirements for workplace welfare facilities, including: sufficient toilets and washbasins with hot and cold water, soap, and drying facilities; drinking water; rest areas (including facilities for pregnant women and nursing mothers); facilities for eating; changing and storing facilities where necessary; and appropriate seating. These facilities must be kept clean and in working order.')
